<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Adonnisninaste</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Apr 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>DoT damage has absolutly nothing to do with aggro IMO.  Flame Lick vs. BoU should be a perfect example of this, Flame Lick will actually give a Druid more aggro than our 64 DoT.  Counters have nothing to do with it either if you ask me, because only DIS/CUR/POI DoTs add counters because they can be cured (I don't believe you can cure other types of PC Dots, but I'm no expert either).  Yet Druid Mag/Fire doesn't add counters, but can still hold very good aggro.<br />
<br />
My assumption at this point, is aggro is coded into spells.  From a DoT perspective, poison would have to be the most aggro.  Fire would make sense for a close second.  Curse and Diesease following close behind.  The only way damage would be brought into the equasion is if two different people casted the same type DoT of different damage levels.<br />
<br />
Everyone used to think our Poison line gave us huge aggro due to the initial DD involved with the older DoTs.  But if that were the case, then Disease DoTs wouldn't be such low aggro even though their DD is somewhat smaller.  All that said, nobody really knows for sure.  But every Shaman should be wary of their POI DoTs and the aggro they give.  We don't need to manage aggro with DIS or CURSE, but then again, we never cast DIS unless soloing either /shrug<br />
<br />
Thats my story, and I'm sticking with it <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="big grin" smilieid="4" /><br />
<br />
Spraggon<br />
Bristlebane</p>
	
	
	
	
	
