	Location: Portland, OR
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Adonnisninaste</b><br /><i>Counters have nothing to do with it either if you ask me, because only DIS/CUR/POI DoTs add counters because they can be cured (I don't believe you can cure other types of PC Dots, but I'm no expert either).  Yet Druid Mag/Fire doesn't add counters, but can still hold very good aggro.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Anyone who has played long enough to remember when they added the disease counters to slow knows that counters can and do add aggro to spells. Disease doesn't seem to add much with the counters anymore because they changed it. Poison counters on the other hand are still pretty high aggro. The proof is actually pretty easy to see if you compare a few spells.<br />
<br />
Compare malos to tash. Malos debuffs by more, does multiple resists and yet is almost no aggro. Seems clear that resist debuffs gerenate very little aggro. Tash on the other hand has posion counters on it and seems to generate a pretty substantial amount of aggro. The obvious conclusion is that the posion counters add aggro.<br />
<br />
Now don't get me wrong the counters alone aren't the only cause of the problem. Take flame lick for example, weak as heck dot and no counters but as noted generates descent amount of aggro. What it does also have tho is an ac debuff on it. Which just happens to be one of the components on cripple too which in my experience is a pretty high aggro spell too. Several of the druid/ranger dots have debuff components on them.<br />
<br />
Even so I still think that per amount of damage done dots generate alot more aggro than nukes. Is it because the aggro each tick is equal to the damage done by the spell so far or even the total damage the spell will do? I don't know. The ony thing I do know is that it is definitely more aggro. I can chain cast nukes for significantly more dps and generate noticably less aggro.</p>
	
	
	
