	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Adonnisninaste</b><br /><i>...My assumption at this point, is aggro is coded into spells.  From a DoT perspective, poison would have to be the most aggro.  Fire would make sense for a close second.  Curse and Diesease following close behind.  The only way damage would be brought into the equasion is if two different people casted the same type DoT of different damage levels...</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I am not sure, i agree with your assumption about different spell types giving different aggro by default, but it's certainly true SOE can define different aggro formulas for separate spells.<br />
<br />
Remember the fuzz about heal aggro for CHs and the comparable heal aggro of direct heals (especially druid ones)? There was a lot of complaining, when player analysis seem to show a 3.000 HP direct heal could draw more aggro than a 7.500 HP CH. It is a while ago, so my memory is foggy but i think SOE tweaked the formulas to calm the angry mobs <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="big grin" smilieid="4" />.<br />
<br />
But i would guess, such 'special' formulas are only applied for special spells, that need different form of aggro. Most spells probably follow a limited set of default formulas, as i can't imagine SOE defining 100s of different formulas for every single spell.<br />
<br />
If counters have or have not a direct impact on aggro (my ASSumption would be they have some impact), i don't know or care. But in practice i know (from game experience), that poison DOTs draw vastly higher aggro compared to similar curse DOTs or DD spells. That should be fixed.</p>
	
	
	
