	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Giac</b><br /><i>I too think people give counters too much weight. Every spell in fact adds counters of some type(if you look up dispells you can clearly see how many counters they dispell).<br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'm sorry but this is wrong. Dispells do not work on counter. Disease, poison and curse are the only counters in the game. If you look them up in lucy dispells do have a number listed after them like cures have but that doesn't mean that they mean the same thing. In the case of dispells the number is apparently a level modifier which increases the chance of the dispell working.<br />
<br />
Counters and cures are always 100% consistant and repeatable on thier results. If a cure spell cures a particular spell in one cast it will always cure it in one cast. Blood of nadox will always cure Bab's ae in fire on everone in the group in 1 cast. Dispell are not consistant by any means. Sometimes they dispell nothing, sometimes they dispell multiple things. Sometime they skip the first buff and dispell ones past them. That is a fundimental difference between the 2 and a clear indication to me that they do not use counters.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><br />
Spells have a certain aggro value attached, regardless of the counters and when you refer to a Malos to Tash comparison as proof, I can simply tell you to compare Cripple to Tash. Cripple, as we all know, doesn't add any poison counters, yet it's at least as much aggro.<br />
<br />
From the beginning poison DoTs have been coded to generate huge aggro and every new spell that they add of the line is basically copied over first, before they change a few numbers like Damage/tick etc.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>While I can't say your definitively wrong about this I don't agree with this either. It just seems like looking for an answer someplace else because you don't like the obvious and contradicts experience and the patch msg of when disease counters where added to slow. It was specifically stated that the counters where generating aggro and that it was being fixed. When Sk's complained about loosing disease cloud as a way of holding aggro the response was we didn't intend that but we'll make new spells for you to generate aggro.<br />
<br />
Those spells are another thing that lead me to beleive your incorrect. If you look at spells like terror of thule <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=3405&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.ht...405&amp;source=Live</a> they do nothing but add aggro yet they have an effect slot to do that. Assuming you could set an aggro value for the spell like you set a mana cost for the spell why would you need to add an effect to the spell to add aggro? That just wouldn't really make any sense to me.<br />
<br />
Don't get me wrong I'm not saying that counters are the only source of aggro on dots. As I've said before the issue is complicated because there are so many variations on dots. initial dmg, no initial dmg, debuff components for all sorts of different things etc. Even so beyond the counters, debuffs and other complications I do beleive there is something probably in the way they calculate aggro from dots, not a property of the spells, that point for point of damage they generate more aggro than nukes or melee dmg.<br />
<br />
As for the specific example of cripple I attribute the aggro on cripple to the ac debuff on it which just happens to be on ranger/druids immolate dots too. There have been other procs/spells that debuff ac and they have been noted as high aggro spells too. The fact that other spells with out counters can generate aggro doesn't mean that counters aren't a source of aggro on spells that include them. There are obviously multiple ways for spells to generate aggro. The stun effect of stun spells has been tested to generate aggro and is commonly accepted that the stun effect it's self generates aggro yet other spells can and do generate aggro too.</p>
	
	
	
