<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>jzak</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>taraddar</b><br /><i><br />
Those spells are another thing that lead me to beleive your incorrect. If you look at spells like terror of thule <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=3405&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.ht...405&amp;source=Live</a> they do nothing but add aggro yet they have an effect slot to do that. Assuming you could set an aggro value for the spell like you set a mana cost for the spell why would you need to add an effect to the spell to add aggro? That just wouldn't really make any sense to me.<br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>If you had an internal means of setting hate values, would you want to make it public to everyone?  If players knew the exact hate values that every spell generated, then they could exploit situations.  <br />
<br />
If you look at the "Raw Data" tab on the spells, you'll see there's a lot of information there.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spellraw.html?id=4901&amp;source=Live" target="_blank">http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spellraw...901&amp;source=Live</a><br />
<br />
There are 12 "slots" in which effects can take place for a spell.  All spells use slots.  If you look at attrib1 for Daluda's Mending, it's a value of 0.  If you look at base1 it's 1550.  Obviously an attrib value of 0 means "alter hitpoints" and the related base value is how much it is altered.  Now look at any DD spell and attrib1 is 0 and base1 is the value of the nuke, but negative, since it alters hitpoints negatively.  That's why heals are sometimes based upon DD templates in the history, since DDs and heals are the same kind of spell; one gives hitpoints and one takes them away.<br />
<br />
For SK aggro spells attrib1 is 92 (alter hate attribute) and base1 is the value of the hate to be added.  Any spell or ability that directly affects hate will have an attrib value of 92 in its raw data page.<br />
<br />
There are still about 22 values that are labeled as "unknown" and one of those could be how much "internal" hate a spell generates.  The last 6 unknown listings are for spell resist values and such during PVP and for categorization in the database.<br />
<br />
For heals and direct damage spells, the hate they generate may be in the legacy code.  Something like if a wizard lands a nuke for 1800, then X% of that value is added to that wizard's hate value on the mob's hate list.  I figure the same for heals, but at a lesser percentage.  Some spells don't do damage or heal damage, so hate has to be calculated a different way.  I would assume an internal value is set somewhere for the line of spells and kept at that value for the entire line.  From a programming perspective, that's the easiest alternative to putting in a specific calculation for each class of spells.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=aa04df70cd6993f17dc6dcc6e0f2e0cf&amp;postid=263441">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=aa04df70cd6993f17dc6dcc6e0f2e0cf&amp;do=getip&postid=263441">Logged</a></div>
	
	<!-- / message -->
		
	</td>
</tr>
